INTRO¶

It is a well-known fact in politics that elected officials should not only be judged by what they say, but more importantly by what they do. To this end, little is more useful than a Member of Parliament's actual voting beheavior when in office. The work of Lucioni (2013), for example, was able to show an increasing degree of political polarization in the US Senate voting relationships over time.

While voting behvior analysis has been around for a while now, very little has been done in the French context as voting data was not readily available to researchers. In recent years, however, the French National Assembly has made available all kinds of data as part of its "Open Government" effort among which are all recorded votes spanning the previous legislature (2012 - 2017) which can be downloaded as an XML file.

The 14th legislature (June 2012 - early 2017) of the French National Assembly, under President Franois Hollande (Socialist Party), was a bumpy ride to say the least. Indeed, the government took a fairly liberal turn starting in 2014, which angered some MPs from the majority, some of whom even seceded from the majority and refused to back the government's legislative proposals. I hope to be able to visualize this in my project.

Research Questions¶

My two main motivating questions for this project are the following:

Can we observe shifts in political alliances and allegiances throughout the 2012 - 2016 French legislative exercise via voting-based networks?

Can MPs' historical voting behaviors be used to determine whom are the most influential / central nodes in the MP network?

I start by providing a quick discussion of the (tedious) data wrangling process (done separately for the sake of space). I then move on to the descriptive network analysis of yearly voting behaviors among MPs and discuss a simple way to sparsify the networks in order to make them more manageable and relevant for analysis. My visual results are quite unconclusive due to network visualisation limitations.
I then present a simple and context-relevant model of node centrality. Using a 2 waves model of influence propagation, I am able to rank MPs according to their political gravitas.

Some quick and basic useful facts about the French National Assembly:¶

  • Members of Parliaments (Dputs) are elected for 5-years mandates shortly after the Presidential election. Because of the timing of the two elections, the President's political party usually gets a majority of the seats at the National Assembly and can therefore efficiently govern throughout his mandate.

  • The National Assembly is composed of 577 MPs. However, it is quite typical that an MP does not sit in the National Assembly for 5 years for several reasons:

    • MPs can become ministers, and therefore leave their seat to their substitute/alternate MP
    • Some MP's mandates are revoked for electoral fraud or misbehavior and another "partial" election sometimes takes place.

  • The President of the National Assembly never votes. As we will see, this observation is quite important for the upcoming analysis.

Data Cleaning¶

(more details available in Vote_Assemblee_Nationale_Adjacency_Matrix.ipynb and Generate_Data.ipynb) in this project's <a href = "https://github.com/vviers/AN-Project"> Github repo </a>).¶

The Data Cleaning portion of this project was very long and tedious because of the way the XML data was stored.

  • I started by downloading the XML file from the <a href = "http://data.assemblee-nationale.fr/">National Assembly's open data website </a> and scrapping each recorded ballot's ID, date, and basic info.

  • I then shortlisted a list of 129 most important ballots i.e. those concerning the entierty of a law proposal. I am therefore excluding the thousands of votes on very specific amendments and where only a couple dozen MPs (max!) vote. Typically these ballots start with "l'ensemble de la proposition de loi..." or "la proposition de loi..."(in list_ballots.csv).

  • Then, I looped over the XML file in order to collect, for each of the aforementionned important ballots, the list of MPIDs present and whether they voted for or against the law proposal (or whether they abstained). I was then able to create a symmetric adjacency matrix $D$ for each ballot where $[D]{ij} = 1$ if MPs i and j voted the same way.

  • Finally, I downloaded a list of MPs that matched a MP's administrative ID with her real name and added this information to my adjacency matrices.

All resulting adjacency matrices csv are stored in: '/adjacency_matrices/data{YEAR}_vote{NUM_VOTE}.csv'

**A final note on the data**: I was not able to match each MP with her political party which would have been very interesting and is left for future work. Being able to color each node according to their political affiliation could really help visualization. For now, I am only able to "manually" check my results (also known as googling).

It might be worth stopping here to make the data building strategy as clear as possible since several approaches are possible. For example, what I originally did was to only focus on MPs who had voted in all ballots and drop those who had missed a ballot. However, this approach made me loose a significant amount of MPs.

What I do: Each MP who voted at least once throughout the year is included in the yearly matrix. This procedure is less robust to events like an MP being revoked in the middle of the year, but this allows me to maximize the size of my networks.

Building Yearly Adjacency Matrices¶

For now, we have an unweighted adjacency matrix for each ballot $b$ i.e.

$$ D_b = \begin{bmatrix} d_{11} & d_{12} & d_{13} & \dots & d_{1n} \\ d_{21} & d_{22} & d_{23} & \dots & d_{2n} \\ \vdots \\ d_{n1} & d_{n2} & d_{n3} & \dots & d_{nn} \end{bmatrix} $$

where $D_b$ is the square and diagonal adjacency matrix of size $(n \times n)$ with $n$ the total number of MPs under consideration for ballot $b$:

$$[D_b]_{ij} = 1, \quad \text{if MP i and MP j voted in the same way (For, Against, Abstention)}$$ and zero otherwise.

By assumption, we do not allow self-loops:

$$[D_b]_{ii} = 0, \quad \forall i$$

Things start getting more interesting once we're adding all adjacency matrices together over the course of a year and dividing the resulting matrix by the total number of ballots during the year:

$$P = \frac{1}{B}\sum_{b = 1}^B D_b$$ where $B$ is the total number of ballots in a given year.

It is easy to see that the entries of matrix P will be equal to the empirical frequencies of similar voting for any two MPs i and j:

$$[P]_{ij} = \frac{\sum_{b = 1}^B [D_b]_{ij}}{B} = \frac{\text{# of times i and j voted the same way}}{\text{# of ballots}}$$

This, as we will see later, could be roughly interpreted as the probability (or historical frequency to be more precise) that MP i and j will vote in the same way.

Let us note that these "probabilities" will be slightly downward biased since MPs are sometimes simply not present at each ballot (and get a row of 0 on these ballots by default).

The following function yearly_matrix() creates such yearly matrix $P$ from a list of matrices $D$:

In [254]:
def yearly_matrix(ballots, probability = True):
    """returns a numpy adjacency matrix of all MPs on a given year.
    if probability = True ==> returns a matrix with empirical frequencies in (0, 1) of similar voting behavior."""
    matrices = [np.array(i) for i in ballots]
    fulladj = sum(matrices)
    if (probability == False):
        return fulladj
    else : return fulladj/len(ballots)

NB: yearly_matrix(., probability = False) would simply return the matrix with the total number of times two MPs voted the same way.

Three main "outliers":

*Henri Plagnol*: was elected in the summer of 2012 but his mandate was revoked in October 2012 after he was found to have cheated during the campaign.

*Jean-Philippe Nilor*: Martiniquais Independentist (one of France's overseas territory) ==> not aligned with any mainstream party.

*Jean-Pierre Decool*: from the independent right, but joined the main opposition party from which he seceded along with 60-ish other MPs from November 2012 to January 2013.

All of the above 3 MPs seem good 'candidates' for non-standard voting behavior i.e. outliers.

The diameter of the network is 2. This makes a lot of sense: as soon as at least two MPs from usually diverging groups agree on at least one occasion, the graph will be connected.

Density: $\frac{2 \times |E|}{|V|(|V|-1)} \approx 0.935$

The graph is very dense since most pairs of MPs at least voted the same way on one occasion over the year. Another way of interpreting this number is that only $6.5 \%$ of all pairs of MP never voted the same way in 2012.

For now, then, a key takeaway of the analysis is that we should figure out a way to "sparsify" the network so that it's easier to see patterns.

One way of decreasing the density of the network is to delete edges whose weights fall below a certain threshold. For example, using a threshold of 0.3 :

In the following subsection, I try to get a little bit more formal about this choice of threshold and the sparsification process.¶

"Sparsity"/Normalization of the Networks.¶

As the above exploration made clear, imposing some degree of sparsity on our networks can go a long way in making our graphs more interpretable and useful.

Though I am focusing on making the networks sparse via setting edges under a specified threshold to 0, let us note that many other methods could be used to get to the same results e.g. imposing a maximum degree for each node.

First, let's explore how the value of our threshold affects the density of our network.¶

I start by making a little twist to the yearly matrix function defined above to allow it to set all edges under a given threshold to 0.

In [271]:
def yearly_sparse_matrix(ballots, threshold):
    matrices = [np.array(i) for i in ballots]
    fulladj = sum(matrices)/len(ballots)
    fulladj[fulladj < threshold] = 0
    return fulladj

We are now ready to explore how our choice of threshold affects our graph. I am moslty interested in:

  • the density of the graph. This is what I would like to reduce in order to make the analysis more manageable.
  • the number of isolate nodes (not connected to any other node) that I will have to drop by setting too-high a threshold thus loosing information.

Ideally, I would like to find the right tradeoff between the two.

In [273]:
# Impact of thresholds

results = pd.DataFrame(np.arange(0, 1, .05), columns = ['threshold'])
k = 2012
for j in [ballots2012, ballots2013, ballots2014, ballots2015, ballots2016]:
    num_isolates = []
    density = []
    for i in np.arange(0, 1, .05):
        ballot = nx.from_numpy_matrix(yearly_sparse_matrix(j, threshold = i))
        num_isolates.append(len(nx.isolates(ballot)))
        density.append(nx.density(ballot))
    results['num_isolates_{}'.format(k)] = num_isolates
    results['density_{}'.format(k)] = density
    k += 1
In [279]:
results.plot(x="threshold", y = ["density_2012", "density_2013", "density_2014",
                                 "density_2015", "density_2016"], figsize = (6, 6),
             xticks=np.arange(0, 1, .1), title = "Network Density");
results.plot(x="threshold", y = ["num_isolates_2012", "num_isolates_2013", "num_isolates_2014",
                                 "num_isolates_2015", "num_isolates_2016"], figsize = (6, 6),
             xticks=np.arange(0, 1, .1), title = "Number of Isolates");

As the above simulation show, yearly networks are generally made much sparser when we drop edges of below .3. What this means is that a relatively high number of MPs agree less than 30% of the time. This seems to be a common feature across years: networks' densities all converge to about 50% when we only take into accounts links that represent an agreement more than 30% of the time.

Interestingly enough, the number of isolates (i.e. number of MPs who are not connected to any other MP) seems relatively robust to sparsification up to a threshold of about 50% (although this number is higher in 2014 and 2016). This suggests that most MPs are at least connected to the biggest portion of the network by one relatively strong link.

As we increase the threshold, we can subdivide the graph into smaller subgraphs: e.g. 2013, using a .5 threshold yields 2 subgraphs of length 246 and 324, respectively.

Yearly Analysis¶

For the following analysis, I will use a threshold value of 50% i.e. an edge between MP i and MP j exists only if MP i and MP j have voted similarily on at least 50% of a given year's ballots. As observed above, this should make visualization significantly easier while keeping most of the MPs in the networks once we drop isolates.

A Simple — and context-relevant! — Measure of Centrality¶

It is fairly easy using the Networkx library to compute classic measures of centrality (Katz centrality, PageRank, eigenvalue centrality, etc...) for the National Assembly network.

However, I am here offering a simple model that is context-relevant. That is, it has a direct interpretation in the context of the National Assembly.

The Lobbyist Model¶

Setup¶

Let the (1 x N) vector $v_t$ represent the outcome of a vote at time t where $[v_{t}]_i = 1$ if MP i votes in favor of the law and 0 otherwise.

Imagine that at time t = 0, all MPs are against a given law, i.e. $v_0 = \overrightarrow{0}$

A lobbyist is only able to "convince" a single MP to become in favor of a law. This MP, however, will then be able to convince her fellow Members of Parliament to vote in favor of the law with probability $p_{ij}$:

$$p_{ij} = \frac{\text{Number of times when i and j voted the same way in the past}}{\text{Total Number of Votes}}$$

resulting in $v_1 = [0, 1, ... 1, ... 0]$ and $v_1 \cdot \iota_N = \text{number of MPs in favor of the law}$. ($\iota_N$ is a vector of ones).

Given information on the historic voting behaviors of all MPs, the lobbyist's goal is therefore to choose this specific MP wisely so that the expected number of MPs who end up in favor of the law is maximized.¶

In other word, the lobbyist is trying to select the most influential MP, measured as the number and strength of links between her and other MPs.

1) Direct effect only (wave_1 influence)¶

Suppose we're only interested in the direct peer effect that "activating" (i.e. convincing) MP$_i$ will have on the outcome of the ballot. Deciding on who to focus is therefore fairly straigtforward: it is enough to sum the rows of the weighted adjacency matrix $P$ in order to obtain each MP's expected direct effect on its peers. We can compute the vector of expected direct effect as:

$$\mathbb{E}[\textit{wave_1_influence}] = P \cdot \iota_N$$

NB: this time, no sparsifying threshold is used.

In [326]:

2) Including Cascading Effects (wave_2 influence)¶

A slightly more sophisticated model arises when we take into consideration the fact that "activated" nodes at t=1 can in turn try and activate the nodes (MPs) they themselves are connected to.

Inspired by the existing literature on such <a href= "https://www.stat.berkeley.edu/~aldous/260-FMIE/Papers/watts.pdf"> 'Cascading Effects' </a>, we can estimate such total effect with the following Monte-Carlo procedure:

  • at $t=0$, only one node $i$ is activated
  • at $t=1$, node $i$ tries to activate all of the nodes it is connected to, with a rate of sucess equal to $p_{ij}$ as defined above. This results in a set of $W_1$ activated nodes ($i$ included), with $1 \leq W_1 \leq (D_{i+} + 1)$ where $D_{i+}$ is the outdegree of node $i$.
  • at $t=2$, all $(W_1 - 1)$ newly activated nodes in turn get a chance to try and activate their unactivated neighbours, which in turn leads to a total of $W_2$ activated nodes with $W_1 \leq W_2 \leq D_{i+, length \leq 2}$. Where $D_{i+, length \leq 2}$ is the number of nodes that are at most length-two paths away from node 1.

In practice, because of the very high density of the graph, the proportion of activated nodes after 2 waves will be very close to 100% for most of the nodes in the network. It is also very unlikely that a MP will change her mind in wave 2 after only one of her peers has "activated" her. I therefore impose a wave_2 activation threshold $\Theta$ whereby node is activated in wave_2 only if it has been sucessfully activated by more than $\Theta$ neighbours.

Intuitively, then, a higher $\Theta$ means that it is harder for a given node to be activated in the second wave (it raises the cost of activating a node in wave_2).

In practice, let us also note that too-high a threshold will lead to no further influence propagation in wave 2: $$\lim_{\Theta \to \infty}\mathbb{E}[W_2 \mid \Theta] = \mathbb{E}[W_1]$$

I limit myself to 2 waves here, for simplicity.

The following function, simulate_cascade, makes the above simulation operational.

In [328]:
def simulate_cascade(MP_id, sparsify, num_rep = 10, sec_wave_threshold = 0):
    
    """
    Takes in:
    - MP_id = the position of a given MP in the weighted adjacency matrix P
    - sparsify = see yearly_sparse_matrix()
    - num_rep = number of simulation for each MP (length of output array)
    - sec_wave_threshold = number of activation by fellow MPs needed for an MP to be indirectly activated (2nd wave).
    
    Returns:
    - an array of size (1 x num_rep) containing simulated 2-wave influence of a given MP (number of
    activated MPs after the second wave).
    """
    
    P = yearly_sparse_matrix(allballots, sparsify)
    
    all_estimates = [] # to store the value at each rep
    
    for r in range(num_rep): # do it num_rep times
        
        result = (np.random.uniform(0, 1, len(P)) <= P[MP_id]) # first wave
        
        if (np.count_nonzero(result)==0): # Handle case where no node is activated after the first iteration
             all_estimates.append(1)
        
        else:
            final_results = np.random.uniform(0, 1, (len(np.where(result == 1)[0]), len(P))) <= P[result]
            final_results[0, MP_id] = 1 # to make sure that the initial activated node is accounted for
        
            all_estimates.append((np.count_nonzero((final_results[:, np.logical_not(result)
                                                                 ].sum(axis = 0)) >= sec_wave_threshold) # second wave activations 
                                  + np.count_nonzero(result))) # + first wave activations = total activs.
    
    return np.array(all_estimates)

As mentionned before, as the threshold for wave_2 activation increases, the overall influence of each MP converges to her wave_1 influence (no additional node is activated in wave_2). Convergence happens more of less quickly depending on an MP's wave_1 influence:

$$\lim_{\Theta \to \infty}\mathbb{E}[W_2 \mid \Theta] = \mathbb{E}[W_1]$$

Monte-Carlo Simulation¶

I now estimate each MP's wave_2 influence using the following process:

For all MPs:

  • simulate 10 random cascades (see above)
  • store the mean and standard deviation $\sigma$ of those 10 simulations
  • compute standard errors as: $SE(\text{Wave_2_influence}) = \frac{\sigma}{\sqrt{10}} $

I present results for different choices of $\Theta$ : $\Theta \in [2, 10, 25, 50, 100]$.

Figuring out a systematic way to optimally choose this parameter would however be very interesting.

As seen before, using too small a $\Theta$ is both unrealistic and useless because it causes most nodes to consistently activate the full network and therefore most MPs are tied for first place.

Looking at higher values of theta (50 and 100), however, we can check the performance of our model:

Interestingly enough, Marc Dolez, Andr Chassaigne, Roger-Grard Schwartzenberg and Marie-George Buffet are all members of the "far-left" (that is, further left than the government party)!

What this suggests seems counterintuitive at first: According to our 2_waves model, the lobbyist should target MPs that are not from the majority. This somehow makes sense if you remember that the "far left" is both strongly connected to the center left (i.e. the government) on some societal issues, and part of the opposition on most other issues (although probably not for the same reasons). Therefore, our simple model would suggest that their influence/centrality is greater!

Being able to split votes by ballot themes (economic, social, etc.) could help investigate this mechanism further.

Investigating the link between wave_1 influence and wave_2 influence.¶

Let's start by plotting the relationship between MP's expected first wave influence and (simulated) expected second wave influence:

I also plot 95% confidence intervals (in light blue) computed as $\bar{X} +/- 2.228 * SE$ (using the t-distribution with df 10)

and fit a degree 2 polynomial to the plot.

In [353]:
# Get 95% Confidence Interval for our estimated 2nd wave effects

def plot_reg_waves(theta):
    ranking["ci_up"] = ranking["Estimated_2_Waves_Influence_{}".format(theta)] + 2.228 * (ranking["wave2se_{}".format(theta)])
    ranking["ci_down"] = ranking["Estimated_2_Waves_Influence_{}".format(theta)] - 2.228 * (ranking["wave2se_{}".format(theta)])

    # Plot & Fit
    plt.figure(figsize = (20, 10))
    sns.regplot(ranking["Expected_Direct_Influence"], ranking["Estimated_2_Waves_Influence_{}".format(theta)], ci=None,
                scatter_kws = {"color":"r", "alpha":.5}, line_kws = {"color":"black", "alpha":.1}, order = 2);

    # Plot C.I.
    plt.vlines(x = ranking["Expected_Direct_Influence"],
               ymin = ranking["ci_down"], ymax = ranking["ci_up"],
               alpha = .1, color = 'blue');
    
    
    # Plot  

    plt.ylabel(r"$ \hat{\mathbf{E}}$[Wave 2 Influence]");
    plt.xlabel(r"$ \mathbf{E}$[Wave 1 Influence]");
    plt.title(r"$\Theta$ = {}".format(theta))
In [354]:
[plot_reg_waves(i) for i in [2, 10]];

As expected, for small (and unrealistic) $\Theta$s, most MPs have close to 100% influence over their peers after 2 waves of propagation. Nothing very interesting can be said about it...

Let us note that MPs with a very small wave_1 influence also have a smaller wave_2 influence with generally high variability which is unsurprising.

In [355]:
[plot_reg_waves(i) for i in [25, 50, 100]];

Using higher $\Theta$, our results are more interesting.

Generally speaking, more influence over your direct neighbors is associated with more influence after 2 waves (see degree 2 polynomial OLS fits in light grey). However, we see that the nodes with the highest wave_2 influence are not necessarily those with the strongest direct influence. This is especially salient using $\Theta = 50$.

Intuitively, observations lying above the line of best-fit are those with relatively "few" direct influence on other nodes, but whose connected nodes are themselves endowed with a lot of influence over the network. Conversely, nodes lying below the line are relatively very well connected but their connections themselves have less impact on their peers.

At $\Theta = \{50, 100\}$, we observe that, as predicted, MPs with too low wave_1 influence lie on the 45 line (i.e. their wave_2 influence equals their wave_1 influence, see above).

We can clearly identify two main clusters as $\Theta$ increases, which I suspect correspond to the two main political parties.

Let's plot a couple of MP names on the $\Theta = 50$ in order to check whether those two clusters indeed corresponds to political parties.¶

very_high = ranking.loc[(ranking["Estimated_2_Waves_Influence_50"] > 520), :]
below_below = ranking.loc[((ranking["Expected_Direct_Influence"] < mean_wave_1) & (ranking["Estimated_2_Waves_Influence_50"] < mean_wave_2)), :]
above_below = ranking.loc[((ranking["Expected_Direct_Influence"] > mean_wave_1) & (ranking["Estimated_2_Waves_Influence_50"] < mean_wave_2)), :]

We indeed have:

  • Pierre Morage, Christian Kert, Sauveur Gandolfi-Scheit are from the center-right, main opposition party.
  • William Dumas, Jean-Pierre Allossery are from the majority center-left party. Emilienne Poumirol and Robert Olive too, but they have only been MPs for 2 years! It therefore makes sense that they have relatively less direct impact than their peers but roughly the same wave_2 influence (their are connected to the majority party). Jean-Claude Gouget became a minister after 1 year as a MP.
  • Marc Dolez and Gaby Charroux are communists, as mentionned before.

$\Longrightarrow$ As a conclusion, we can see that projecting MPs into their wave_1 / wave_2 influence produces a very good clustering of MPs according to their political parties! The Lobbyist model is therefore quite useful in that regard.¶

Again, being able to color MPs according to their political parties would really be a great next step...

ANNEX: All Years Together Network EDA¶

I start by plotting the influence of our choice of threshold on several degree statistics:

In [318]:
average_connect = []
max_connect = []
median_connect = []
min_connect = []
num_isolates = []
for i in np.arange(0, 1, .05):
    ballot = nx.from_numpy_matrix(yearly_sparse_matrix(allballots, i))
    num_isolates.append(len(nx.isolates(ballot)))
    
    ballot.remove_nodes_from(nx.isolates(ballot))
    
    average_connect.append(np.mean(list(nx.average_degree_connectivity(ballot).values())))
    
    max_connect.append(np.max(list(nx.average_degree_connectivity(ballot).values())))
    
    median_connect.append(np.median(list(nx.average_degree_connectivity(ballot).values())))
    
    min_connect.append(np.min(list(nx.average_degree_connectivity(ballot).values())))
    
    
    
results = pd.DataFrame(np.transpose([np.arange(0, 1, .05), average_connect,
                                     max_connect, median_connect,
                                     min_connect, num_isolates]),
                       columns = ["threshold", "average_connect", "max_connect", "median_connect", "min_connect", "num_isolates"])
In [319]:
results.plot(x="threshold", figsize = (10, 10));
